WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:17.120
Hi, friends. Welcome back to the last Data Science Hangout of 2022. I hope you all are

00:00:17.120 --> 00:00:22.320
having a great week. If you're joining us for the first time today, thanks for coming

00:00:22.320 --> 00:00:28.240
to Hangout. I'm Rachel. It's so nice to meet you. I see a bunch of people in the waiting

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:33.759
room, so let me just press the Admit All button one second here. But this is an open space

00:00:33.759 --> 00:00:40.320
for the whole data science community to connect and chat about data science leadership, questions

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:44.680
you're facing, and getting to learn about what's going on in the world of data across

00:00:44.680 --> 00:00:50.840
different industries. So together, we're all dedicated to creating a welcoming environment

00:00:50.840 --> 00:00:56.560
for everybody, and we love to hear from everyone, no matter your level of experience or your

00:00:56.560 --> 00:01:02.000
area of work as well. So there's always three ways that you can ask questions here in this

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:10.440
space and also provide your perspective. You can jump in by raising your hand on Zoom.

00:01:10.440 --> 00:01:15.680
You can put questions into the Zoom chat, and feel free to put a little star next to

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:20.739
it if you want me to read it if you're in a coffee shop or your dog's barking or something

00:01:20.739 --> 00:01:27.779
like that. And then third, we also have a Slido link where you can ask questions anonymously.

00:01:27.779 --> 00:01:34.220
And I bet Hannah is sharing that in the chat here in just a second. If this is your first

00:01:34.220 --> 00:01:40.220
Hangout today, I thought it'd be nice to see maybe have you say hi by putting a one into

00:01:40.220 --> 00:01:47.820
the chat. And if you've been here before, put a two. For those who have been here before,

00:01:47.820 --> 00:01:54.459
many times we'd love to all help welcome you in as well. And so just to let everybody

00:01:54.459 --> 00:01:59.620
know, we do share the recordings of each session up to the pause at YouTube. So you can always

00:01:59.620 --> 00:02:06.580
go back and rewatch or find helpful resources. We do also have a LinkedIn group for the Hangout

00:02:06.580 --> 00:02:12.660
too if it helps you connect with each other. One more thing on the topic of recordings

00:02:12.660 --> 00:02:19.100
and resources. I am hoping to take a quick pulse from the community this week on what

00:02:19.100 --> 00:02:24.740
has worked well for you, what hasn't and any suggestions you have for next year. So we'll

00:02:24.740 --> 00:02:30.460
share that link in the chat in a second too. But I so appreciate the thoughtful feedback

00:02:30.460 --> 00:02:35.660
that so many of you have provided already, not only in a survey, but throughout the year

00:02:35.660 --> 00:02:41.899
as well. So with all of that, thank you so much for being here. Let's jump in. This is

00:02:41.899 --> 00:02:47.979
the first time my co-host is in the same building as me, not in the same room, but

00:02:47.979 --> 00:02:54.779
so happy to be joined by my co-host today, JJ Laird, CEO and founder of Posit. So I throw

00:02:54.779 --> 00:03:02.100
in the formerly known as RStudio. Thanks for joining us, JJ. I'd love to have you introduce

00:03:02.100 --> 00:03:07.660
yourself and share a bit about your background and maybe also let us know something you like

00:03:07.660 --> 00:03:17.740
to do outside of work too. Okay. Well, very briefly, I'm obviously do lots of software

00:03:17.740 --> 00:03:22.699
engineering and product development now, but when I was younger, I studied political science

00:03:22.699 --> 00:03:29.339
and I got very interested in data analysis. But I could took a deep detour from that and

00:03:29.339 --> 00:03:33.820
got into writing software and worked on lots of different software products. And about

00:03:33.899 --> 00:03:40.619
I think it was 11 or 12 years ago, I kind of became aware of R and I was actually looking

00:03:40.619 --> 00:03:45.899
for opportunities to work on open source software. And I thought it was tremendously cool that sort

00:03:45.899 --> 00:03:50.699
of the thing that got me interested in software in the first place and kind of the first thing

00:03:50.699 --> 00:03:57.580
I wanted to do, which was data analysis, had this really, really vital open source project

00:03:57.580 --> 00:04:01.979
associated with it. So I kind of just said, let me get involved with R. And then I've been doing

00:04:01.979 --> 00:04:09.179
that at RStudio and now at Posit for, I think it's been 11 or 12 years. So I started the company

00:04:09.179 --> 00:04:18.459
and I worked on the RStudio IDE. And then I worked quite a bit on R Markdown, a little bit on Shiny,

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:26.859
some stuff related to TensorFlow. And then about two or three years ago, I started a new project

00:04:26.859 --> 00:04:33.260
called Cordo, which was sort of a re-imagining of R Markdown, both in terms of kind of like,

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:40.299
if we had to do it all over again from the beginning, what would we do? But also to make

00:04:40.299 --> 00:04:46.779
R Markdown multi-language, to make it so it could work for R and Python and Julia and JavaScript and

00:04:46.779 --> 00:04:54.859
kind of not really make it available for anyone who's doing scientific communication or doing

00:04:54.859 --> 00:05:01.579
data analysis of any kind in any language. So that's what I've been working on and continuing

00:05:01.579 --> 00:05:07.660
to work on now. So, and I get my hands in lots of other different projects here at RStudio too.

00:05:07.660 --> 00:05:12.779
But so, and then, oh, what do I like to do outside of work? I like to play Magic the Gathering.

00:05:13.579 --> 00:05:22.700
So. Awesome. Thank you. So I'd love to ask you, what made you so like,

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:29.579
interested in open source initially? Yeah. It was really that I actually worked on the first

00:05:29.579 --> 00:05:36.859
couple big software projects I worked on were proprietary software. And I found it disappointing

00:05:36.859 --> 00:05:45.260
that like proprietary software products kind of get very tied up with the company that sponsors

00:05:45.260 --> 00:05:52.140
them and sort of the fate of that company and the other products that that company might offer or

00:05:52.140 --> 00:05:57.820
who that company gets acquired by really like end up affecting the fate of the projects.

00:05:57.820 --> 00:06:04.540
And I also found that, I mean, some proprietary software is either cheap or free or low cost, but

00:06:04.540 --> 00:06:11.100
there's a certain, you know, impediment to adoption associated with the price that as a,

00:06:11.100 --> 00:06:17.260
you know, as a creative person, I kind of want my work to be available as broadly as possible. So

00:06:17.260 --> 00:06:22.540
I kind of both, it's like make the work available to as many people as possible,

00:06:22.540 --> 00:06:27.179
but also there's like a dimension of like the durability of the work. Is the work going to be

00:06:27.179 --> 00:06:32.619
around in 30 years or 40 years? What are the things that would make it not? So that's what

00:06:32.619 --> 00:06:39.980
made open source appealing to me. I'm seeing a lot of love for Cordo in the chat right now,

00:06:39.980 --> 00:06:43.420
but while we wait just a minute here for questions to come in from everybody.

00:06:44.220 --> 00:06:49.019
I'm also curious, what are you most excited about at Posit in the next year ahead?

00:06:49.660 --> 00:06:54.299
The next year? Well, it's going to be related to Cordo, of course, because that's what I'm

00:06:54.299 --> 00:07:03.100
spending all my time on. I would say that the thing I'm excited about is we're, and you can

00:07:03.100 --> 00:07:09.899
sort of see some of this work in the visual editor that's in our studio. But we really like,

00:07:10.459 --> 00:07:18.140
we recognize that Cordo is really powerful and flexible and actually easy to use for a certain

00:07:18.140 --> 00:07:23.500
subset of users who are very technical and very motivated, but we actually want to make Cordo

00:07:23.500 --> 00:07:30.859
available more broadly. And so working on tooling that both lets technical people collaborate with

00:07:30.859 --> 00:07:36.940
non-technical people over documents, and also lets some less technical people participate in

00:07:37.899 --> 00:07:43.019
using Cordo are the kind of things that I'm focused on for the next

00:07:43.019 --> 00:07:46.299
year. And I'm excited to see those getting realized.

00:07:48.459 --> 00:07:51.820
Awesome. Sam, I see you put a question to the chat. Do you want to jump in?

00:07:52.940 --> 00:07:58.619
Yeah, I just wanted to see what your thoughts were on AI tools like ChatGPT and GitHub.

00:07:59.500 --> 00:08:04.619
Yeah, I think that I'm a little concerned that

00:08:07.260 --> 00:08:13.019
companies are rushing these things out in the sort of excitement and novelty of them and have

00:08:13.019 --> 00:08:24.299
not thought through the implications of their broader use. Something like ChatGPT is not really

00:08:24.299 --> 00:08:33.099
like, the creators of it don't have full control of it. You can see that in the safeguards that

00:08:33.099 --> 00:08:36.700
they attempted to put in, but then you can circumvent the safeguards and get it to tell

00:08:36.700 --> 00:08:43.900
you things that it's not supposed to tell you. So I think things that are happening in AI and

00:08:43.900 --> 00:08:51.820
generative AI specifically are exciting, but I feel like technology companies and technologists

00:08:52.700 --> 00:08:58.059
just sometimes feel like we should do this because we can or we should do this because it's cool

00:08:58.059 --> 00:09:05.340
and haven't thought about the broader social, political, economic implications. So I feel like

00:09:06.059 --> 00:09:12.940
certainly exciting to see us come up with AI that is that powerful, but I think we're going

00:09:12.940 --> 00:09:21.500
a little too fast. That would be my position. Thank you. Olivier, so you also asked a question

00:09:21.500 --> 00:09:27.659
in the chat. You want to jump in? Sure. I was wondering, because I've been doing a lot of

00:09:27.659 --> 00:09:34.380
retrospection lately. Yeah. In hindsight, what is one of the best decisions that you ever made for

00:09:34.380 --> 00:09:44.859
your career, your education? I would say the best decision that I've ever made is probably that,

00:09:46.059 --> 00:09:50.140
and this actually I think has a lot of commonality with talking to a lot of people

00:09:50.140 --> 00:09:56.380
about their careers. I think when I was about in my late 30s, I had been involved in both

00:09:56.380 --> 00:10:02.780
developing software and also starting companies, and I really learned about myself that

00:10:03.099 --> 00:10:09.179
the company part of things, management and the entrepreneurship, and I really

00:10:10.219 --> 00:10:16.780
did not like it all. I did not like it. I didn't enjoy it. I didn't, and so I kind of said,

00:10:17.820 --> 00:10:22.539
I'm happy to be involved in starting companies, but I'm absolutely not going to do that part,

00:10:22.539 --> 00:10:27.820
and I'm going to have to find a partner or other people who are excited about doing that part, and

00:10:27.820 --> 00:10:32.780
what I really want to do is focus on engineering and product development, and I was really, it's

00:10:32.780 --> 00:10:38.299
very easy as a company founder to get pulled into all kinds of other things, and that's what happened

00:10:38.299 --> 00:10:44.219
to me the first two times, and just being super clear about that and saying, I won't even do it

00:10:44.219 --> 00:10:50.460
unless I can satisfy this condition, and then, so I think that's pretty broadly applicable in that a

00:10:50.460 --> 00:10:56.299
lot of us accumulate a lot of responsibility in our careers, and some of it's necessary and

00:10:56.299 --> 00:11:01.820
important for a given role or company, but then eventually being clear about what do I

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:07.500
really like to do and really want to do, and what do I feel like I should do or what is put upon me.

00:11:07.500 --> 00:11:14.380
I know a lot of people now who are in their 40s who have actually managed dozens of people,

00:11:15.020 --> 00:11:18.140
and are like, yeah, I don't really want to do that anymore. I don't ever want to have anyone

00:11:18.140 --> 00:11:21.900
work for me anymore, so I'm going to be really clear about that, and I'm going to walk in, and

00:11:21.900 --> 00:11:25.500
people are going to try to give me people. They're going to try to make me a manager, and I'm not

00:11:25.500 --> 00:11:32.219
going to do it, so I think it applies pretty broadly, but just knowing yourself and setting

00:11:32.219 --> 00:11:38.700
like pretty rigid constraints about like what you're willing to do in the workplace and not, so.

00:11:40.140 --> 00:11:45.260
Thank you. That's awesome. Yeah. Thank you. That's something that's definitely come up

00:11:45.260 --> 00:11:50.780
quite a few times in this space, too, and that like jump to management, and then you lose out

00:11:50.780 --> 00:11:55.900
on the technical side. Yeah, it's a hard one, and everybody's different, and both can be really

00:11:55.900 --> 00:12:01.099
rewarding. I know a lot of people who find management very rewarding, but I know a lot

00:12:01.099 --> 00:12:08.619
of people who find it really alienating, so it's. I see a few anonymous questions that came in, too,

00:12:08.619 --> 00:12:14.219
so I want to make sure I jump over there, and one was will Posit work to make Python as enjoyable

00:12:14.219 --> 00:12:21.099
to use as R? Well, we have a different kind of a special relationship with R in that, you know,

00:12:21.099 --> 00:12:26.700
we have the tidyverse. We've sort of defined this sort of system within the system that's totally

00:12:26.700 --> 00:12:32.140
internally, hopefully as much as possible, totally internally consistent, and it's really like really

00:12:32.140 --> 00:12:36.780
well tooled end-to-end. I don't know that we'll ever be able to have that sort of relationship

00:12:36.780 --> 00:12:42.700
to Python, because Python is, there's just so vast, and people are piecing together so many

00:12:42.700 --> 00:12:48.140
different things from so many different places, so I think we'll make contributions, like we're

00:12:48.140 --> 00:12:55.340
definitely focused right now on like doing Cordo for Python and Shiny for Python. Can we, I just

00:12:55.340 --> 00:13:03.340
don't actually think that any company is big enough to like do for Python what we sort of did for R,

00:13:03.340 --> 00:13:10.059
so I think we'll make it more pleasurable in places, but I don't know that it's going to

00:13:10.059 --> 00:13:19.419
be anything like what we've done with R. Excuse me. You, I see you put a question into the chat

00:13:19.419 --> 00:13:25.099
a bit earlier. Do you want to jump in next? Sure. Hi, JJ. Actually, my question is kind of piggybacking

00:13:25.099 --> 00:13:31.739
on what you just said, so R as a programming language is almost 30 years old, and R versus Python

00:13:31.739 --> 00:13:39.500
is an eternal topic, so where do we see R in the next 10 years? So actually R is even more,

00:13:39.500 --> 00:13:47.820
it's even like over 40 years old, if you count S, which is its precursor. I think what

00:13:47.820 --> 00:13:54.619
we're trying to do with R is, and you can see like a lot of the stuff that we've done, and maybe

00:13:54.619 --> 00:13:59.260
it's not all super visible yet, but like some of the things we've done in the tidyverse in the last

00:13:59.260 --> 00:14:07.900
year have been like focused on like making error messages much better, and so like I feel like

00:14:07.900 --> 00:14:17.260
R has the potential to cross the, like go over the transom from people who are, do not program,

00:14:17.260 --> 00:14:22.859
do not think of themselves as programmers, have not programmed to do successful, you know, kind

00:14:22.859 --> 00:14:28.619
of code-first data science. I think R is actually pretty uniquely positioned to do that, and I feel

00:14:28.619 --> 00:14:34.940
like we kind of are just getting started with that, so the people who today use, you know, they

00:14:34.940 --> 00:14:41.820
may use Excel or SPSS or, you know, Tableau or, you know, they use, they do, they're doing data analysis,

00:14:41.820 --> 00:14:47.979
but they're actually not able to ask and answer all the questions they should. I see R as being

00:14:47.979 --> 00:14:53.900
like fitting right in that spot of the best way for someone who thinks of themselves, I'm a

00:14:53.900 --> 00:15:00.299
biologist, I'm an economist, but I need to answer like difficult questions about data, so I see R

00:15:00.299 --> 00:15:04.460
getting better and better and better in that, in that vector, and that's certainly where, like where

00:15:04.539 --> 00:15:07.900
we're putting our time, at least in the Tidyverse team right now.

00:15:10.780 --> 00:15:17.419
So we're now getting confessions into Slido, too, as someone said, so this is a confession and also

00:15:17.419 --> 00:15:24.059
a call for suggestions. I love dplyr, Shiny, and R, but I'm switching to Python simply because

00:15:24.059 --> 00:15:28.940
it's listed in a lot more jobs, and gives a better starting point for a possible career

00:15:28.940 --> 00:15:34.380
change in other areas of programming, so what would you advise for someone in my position?

00:15:36.460 --> 00:15:41.979
Well, there are a lot of ideas in R that you, you're familiar with, and then some of those

00:15:41.979 --> 00:15:47.500
are carried over to, to different libraries in Python, so you can sort of try to find

00:15:48.140 --> 00:15:53.419
the places in Python and adopt the projects that, there's definitely like some of the,

00:15:54.140 --> 00:16:00.299
I think like Plot9, and I think it's like Sluba, I think, sort of a dplyr-like

00:16:01.260 --> 00:16:06.299
library, like, so there are like Python libraries that are sort of very much inspired by their R

00:16:06.299 --> 00:16:12.539
counterparts. You can adopt those, you can get involved with those. I don't think you're, you're

00:16:12.539 --> 00:16:19.580
going to have quite the same end-to-end experience, but you can, and you can kind of, like I said,

00:16:19.659 --> 00:16:27.580
like, get involved with the projects that you think do in Python what you love so much

00:16:28.140 --> 00:16:32.460
about R, and try to get those, you know, more widely adopted.

00:16:34.299 --> 00:16:38.700
Thank you, I see. Thanks, Jake, for sharing the link to Sluba there in the chat too.

00:16:40.780 --> 00:16:45.900
Alan, I see some plus ones to your question, so I'd love to have you jump in and ask that too.

00:16:46.299 --> 00:16:51.179
Yeah, sure. Hi, my question is about the impact that RStudios had on the community

00:16:51.900 --> 00:16:57.500
over the years. I think it's been really positive in helping the community be welcoming and

00:16:57.500 --> 00:17:03.739
encouraging and open in a way that I think folks agree, and we make lots of jokes about,

00:17:03.739 --> 00:17:09.099
was not necessarily the way, like, when I was a grad student, for example. Was that a conscientious

00:17:09.099 --> 00:17:14.780
orientation? I'm curious about the story of how you came to that kind of contribution in particular,

00:17:15.739 --> 00:17:19.979
and how conscientious it was. Yeah, it was, I was very conscientious. I definitely think,

00:17:19.979 --> 00:17:26.619
you know, a lot of us first encountered the R community in sort of a, like, less friendly mode,

00:17:27.979 --> 00:17:33.979
and I think there was, that was sort of disappointing, like, wow, it'd be great if

00:17:33.979 --> 00:17:37.739
more people felt welcome, and more people felt like they could come in and ask questions and

00:17:37.739 --> 00:17:46.380
succeed. But I would, I would, I would credit primarily Hadley for his orientation around that.

00:17:46.380 --> 00:17:50.619
He is, for those of you that know him or have heard him talk about this sort of stuff, he is

00:17:51.420 --> 00:17:59.339
extremely passionate about inclusiveness and friendliness and welcomingness. Like, he is,

00:17:59.339 --> 00:18:03.339
and he is, I mean, there's a lot of people here who believe in those things,

00:18:03.900 --> 00:18:09.260
but he really set the tone for that, and for the whole community, and for the company. So,

00:18:10.219 --> 00:18:15.020
it's definitely very self-conscious. That's great to hear. Yeah, it's really made an impact.

00:18:16.939 --> 00:18:21.819
Thank you. Yeah. Thank you. Paul, I see you have your hand raised. Do you want to jump in?

00:18:23.339 --> 00:18:29.500
Yeah, sure. Thank you. Thank you, guys. So, I guess my question, well, this is kind of a question,

00:18:29.500 --> 00:18:35.180
but it's also, like, something that being, you know, having discussions with my, sorry, I'm

00:18:35.180 --> 00:18:40.140
moving around the house. I have my newborn daughter. She was just born this Saturday,

00:18:40.140 --> 00:18:47.660
so I'm here, like, taking diapers and everything, whatnot. So, yeah. So, I work for the Panama Canal

00:18:47.660 --> 00:18:57.180
Authority, and the Panama Canal has recently created a data science unit. And so, basically,

00:18:57.900 --> 00:19:03.819
we're, like, 16 people there, and I'm the only one that is a heavy R user, because we're, like,

00:19:03.819 --> 00:19:08.060
divided. It's, like, me against the rest. Well, it's not, like, against, but it's, like, yeah. So,

00:19:08.060 --> 00:19:13.660
we work in many different projects, and basically, everybody else does, you know, everything,

00:19:13.660 --> 00:19:19.739
like, machine learning, and those sort of things in Python, and then I do my thing in R. So,

00:19:20.540 --> 00:19:28.219
my question would be, how much, I mean, there's always a debate, and you always find on the

00:19:28.219 --> 00:19:33.099
internet, like, these papers and discussions, like, whether to use R or Python for machine

00:19:33.099 --> 00:19:40.859
learning, for AI, whatever. And I've seen, you know, all sorts of opinions about it. There's

00:19:40.859 --> 00:19:46.459
people that is, like, okay, Python is better when it comes to AI and machine learning,

00:19:46.859 --> 00:19:54.699
and then R is better for statistical computing, or for computational statistics purposes. Now,

00:19:54.699 --> 00:20:00.619
I'm an actuary, and, you know, I've been using R since I used to work for insurance companies in

00:20:00.619 --> 00:20:09.420
maybe 2006. And, you know, this is probably a testimony also. I've never had, you know,

00:20:09.900 --> 00:20:17.020
the need to, you know, to use Python. I've used R for, you know, almost all my life for doing,

00:20:17.020 --> 00:20:21.339
you know, computational stats and data analysis, and, you know, from all the time series and

00:20:21.339 --> 00:20:28.619
whatnot. So, my question would be, in terms of its, you know, capability of dealing with large

00:20:28.619 --> 00:20:35.819
data sets, in terms of its capability of, you know, for modeling, you know, machine learning,

00:20:36.780 --> 00:20:41.020
machine learning purposes and everything, what would you say that, how would you say that R

00:20:41.020 --> 00:20:46.219
compares to Python? Because that's something I'm always interested in, you know, knowing,

00:20:46.219 --> 00:20:51.579
you know, just because I'm an R, heavy R user. And I'm not saying that Python, I mean, Python,

00:20:51.579 --> 00:20:58.300
both are wonderful tools for data science and everything. But to me, I'm actually getting,

00:20:58.300 --> 00:21:03.180
you know, I'm in my, I'm at Johns Hopkins University, getting a master's degree in data

00:21:03.180 --> 00:21:09.660
science. And, you know, I try to use R as much as I can. I've been exposed to Python, but still,

00:21:10.219 --> 00:21:16.780
I feel that statistical analysis is, it's, I think it's way easier with R than with Python.

00:21:16.780 --> 00:21:22.459
Yeah, it definitely is. I would say statistical analysis, interactive data exploration,

00:21:24.060 --> 00:21:28.699
communicate, you know, kind of creating data products that communicate things that are,

00:21:28.699 --> 00:21:34.619
like R is better than Python at all those things, I think. It is not as strong of, it's not as

00:21:34.619 --> 00:21:42.060
widely used as a language. So, it's not as general purpose. And I think in terms of, like, large data

00:21:42.060 --> 00:21:50.619
sets, I think that mostly that is handled by either, like, external systems you interface with

00:21:50.619 --> 00:21:58.060
or native code. So, like, dplyr or Datatable or DuckDB or Arrow or Spark. There's some means by

00:21:58.060 --> 00:22:04.380
which you're being, you're able to access large data. It's not really confined by the language.

00:22:04.380 --> 00:22:09.979
