00:22:09.979 --> 00:22:14.699
I do think in terms of machine learning, there's a lot of machine learning packages in R. And,

00:22:14.699 --> 00:22:20.859
you know, some of the, like, most important things like XGBoost and stuff work very well in R.

00:22:21.819 --> 00:22:29.660
Python probably has a, like, we have created deep learning interfaces in R, both to TensorFlow and

00:22:29.660 --> 00:22:35.819
Torch. But Python probably does have an edge in deep learning, I would say, in that you can use

00:22:35.819 --> 00:22:40.380
those libraries and there's probably more, like, third part extensions to those things that are

00:22:40.380 --> 00:22:49.739
available. So, but, like, deep learning is one part of, one part of machine learning, one part

00:22:49.739 --> 00:22:55.339
of working with data. And it's not really predominant in some fields. It's really quite

00:22:55.339 --> 00:23:03.339
important, but it's not really predominant. So, I think, you know, I think, like, I think what

00:23:03.339 --> 00:23:10.540
we're hoping to make easy for our users is a world where if you want to use R and it is so much

00:23:10.540 --> 00:23:14.939
easier for so many things, it's very easy for you to make that case. And so, like, things like

00:23:14.939 --> 00:23:20.060
reticulate for interoperability, things like that, you know, we're trying to make it easy to

00:23:20.060 --> 00:23:29.180
make that case. And so, I would say, like, for the things you're doing, R is clearly, clearly better.

