together, you know? So, so that's, that's that. And then lots of opportunities, you know, in,

01:03:13.419 --> 01:03:20.379
in, you know, sales and marketing and, and things like that, that you'll see on our website, but

01:03:21.020 --> 01:03:29.419
yeah. Thank you, JJ. I'm seeing a lot of comments in here that says JJ for president. So

01:03:29.419 --> 01:03:34.620
something to think about here. Okay. One last, one last question. Thank you, Jonathan,

01:03:34.620 --> 01:03:39.340
for the great question here. What are some failures that you have learned from in your

01:03:39.340 --> 01:03:47.820
career and how have you grown from your experience? Yeah. I'd say one failure was

01:03:49.260 --> 01:03:56.139
the second kind of company that I started. I, the first company I started went pretty well

01:03:56.699 --> 01:04:02.699
and I kind of thought that, oh, you know, the, the skill that I was applying there was like,

01:04:02.699 --> 01:04:14.459
I the skill was like I don't want to say this, like coming up with like brand new ways to work

01:04:14.459 --> 01:04:20.300
and brand new ideas is like a skill. And then that's what startup founders do. And I kind of

01:04:20.300 --> 01:04:24.139
like in my second company, like try to create a whole bunch of brand new things, like, oh,

01:04:24.139 --> 01:04:29.100
reimagine your work this way, do this totally different thing that you're doing now. And that

01:04:29.100 --> 01:04:36.219
didn't go very well. And I kind of took from that, like, it's much better to be rooted in

01:04:37.100 --> 01:04:42.139
what you observe people are doing exactly what they're doing and try to make that better.

01:04:42.139 --> 01:04:47.419
So as an example, when we started, I started working in R, I wasn't a data scientist,

01:04:47.419 --> 01:04:52.139
I wasn't an R programmer, and we easily could have said, okay, we're going to reimagine how

01:04:52.139 --> 01:04:56.379
you work with R. We're going to build this brand new interface, forget about the console, forget

01:04:56.379 --> 01:05:03.179
about, but I said, well, there's lots of people using R just this way. And so if I can just make

01:05:03.179 --> 01:05:09.419
that better, then that's like a good foundation. So I think like overreaching in product design

01:05:09.419 --> 01:05:14.379
is something that I definitely paid for in the second company that I started. And I've tried

01:05:14.379 --> 01:05:30.300
to not do that, try to stay close to what people are doing, I'd say. I think I alluded to this

01:05:30.300 --> 01:05:37.580
before, but like, not knowing yourself well, and finding yourself in sort of with responsibilities

01:05:37.979 --> 01:05:42.540
and in a work situation, where you're not like being nourished the way you need to,

01:05:44.699 --> 01:05:51.979
you can end up in that spot, and it's very hard to dig yourself out of it. So yeah, that's happened.

01:05:53.340 --> 01:05:58.300
Thank you. I know I said that was the last question, but I don't want to end on like failure.

01:05:58.780 --> 01:06:07.979
So I know something we talk about at Posit is creating a company that's around in 100 years.

01:06:09.419 --> 01:06:11.580
What do you think is one of the most important

01:06:12.860 --> 01:06:17.899
lessons learned or things that you're thinking about to get us to 100 years from now?

01:06:18.459 --> 01:06:24.219
Well, I think the number one thing was get the right corporate structure. So all the incentives

01:06:24.219 --> 01:06:28.939
are aligned. So that's the only thing we need to worry about. And we're not worried about

01:06:28.939 --> 01:06:40.540
maximizing some short term objective. So that's one. Now, two is going to be leadership succession.

01:06:40.540 --> 01:06:45.419
So it's easy to get caught up in like, oh, hey, you know, there's four or five of us that are

01:06:45.419 --> 01:06:50.300
kind of leading things, and we're making it all work. And then like, yeah, but we're all going

01:06:50.300 --> 01:06:56.620
to get old, you know. And so trying to figure out like over time, who are the people that are

01:06:56.620 --> 01:07:02.939
going to succeed you and giving them opportunities to like even accelerate their learning and bring

01:07:02.939 --> 01:07:08.939
them into the space that you're in is I think where a lot of organizations fail to be sustainable.

01:07:08.939 --> 01:07:12.780
They may be like economically sustainable, they may have the right corporate incentives, but then

01:07:13.340 --> 01:07:17.979
like succession kind of does them in. So that's something where it's not like right on our doorstep,

01:07:17.979 --> 01:07:21.899
but it's something that's on my mind to think about. So.

01:07:23.500 --> 01:07:29.580
Thank you. Thank you so much, JJ, for joining us today and sharing your experience.

01:07:29.580 --> 01:07:36.540
This has been really fun. And thank you all for being a part of the Data Science Hangout today.

01:07:36.540 --> 01:07:42.300
If this was your first one or for the past year and a half or however long we've been doing this,

01:07:42.300 --> 01:07:47.340
thank you for coming to spend time with us all. I hope you and your families have a wonderful

01:07:47.340 --> 01:07:54.620
holiday season and Happy New Year. This is our last Hangout for 2022, but we will be back here

01:07:54.620 --> 01:08:00.939
after a bit of a holiday break. So we'll be back on Thursday, January 12th for the first Hangout of

01:08:00.939 --> 01:08:06.060
2023. Thank you all so much for making this the best part of the week.

